<div class='communityQuestionAndAnswer'>
<div class='communityQuestion'>
<div class='questionText'>
<a href="/questions/1041090-should-we-trust-everything-hugo-is-telling">Should we trust everything Hugo is telling us in this book? For example, I googled the story of compachicos, but it seems it is only fully decribed in &quot;The Man Who Laughs&quot;? Did it exist?</a>
</div>
<div class='communityQAFooter questionFooter'>
<ul class='questionFooterActions'>
<li class='footerItem like'>
<span class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_community_question_1041090'><a rel="nofollow" class="jsLike like_it" href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F63038.The_Man_Who_Laughs">like</a></span>

</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionTimestamp'>
<a href="/questions/1041090-should-we-trust-everything-hugo-is-telling">4 years ago</a>
</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionPermalink'>
<a href="/questions/1041090-should-we-trust-everything-hugo-is-telling">Add your answer</a>
</li>
</ul>
</div>

</div>
<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/58439681-filomena"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1477670980i/58439681._UX100_CR0,30,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/58439681-filomena">Filomena </a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<div class='spoiler'>
This answer contains spoilers…
<span class='spoilerAnswerText'>
<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[
  
    Yes, it did. If you google “Facts about Compachicos, you will find more information. Victor Hugo wrote a novel but the information in it, historical f<a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">…more</a>
    Yes, it did. If you google “Facts about Compachicos, you will find more information. Victor Hugo wrote a novel but the information in it, historical facts, French and English peerage, compachicos, are based on history, not his imagination. Of course one will never know if in fact a child was made to look like the laughing man by compachicos. However, it is my opinion that there were children of peers that were mutulated by them, for the same reason Fermain Clancharlie was. <a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">(less)</a>
  
 <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>
</span>
</div>
</span>
</div>
