<div id="review_3667470012" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3667470012" />
    <a title="J.M. Hushour" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/17463213-j-m-hushour"><img alt="J.M. Hushour" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442964894p2/17463213.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3667470012?book_show_action=true">Dec 02, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="J.M. Hushour" class="user" itemprop="url" name="J.M. Hushour" href="/user/show/17463213-j-m-hushour">J.M. Hushour</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781904999843" href="/book/show/7011760-laughing-man-the">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3667470012" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12814950427865530441">Astonishingly bad, and even the most cursory read of my reviews of everything else Hugo wrote will show you why. I love Hugo! His novels I count among some of the greatest things to ever drip from quill to paper. I even have one of his pieces of art that he himself made from this very novel hanging not six feet from my left shoulder blade!<br/>What the hell?! But, yes, this novel is unabashedly terrible. It was even one of the inspirations for Batman&apos;s nemesis, The Joker and everyone knows I love the</span>
  <span id="freeText12814950427865530441" style="display:none">Astonishingly bad, and even the most cursory read of my reviews of everything else Hugo wrote will show you why. I love Hugo! His novels I count among some of the greatest things to ever drip from quill to paper. I even have one of his pieces of art that he himself made from this very novel hanging not six feet from my left shoulder blade!<br />What the hell?! But, yes, this novel is unabashedly terrible. It was even one of the inspirations for Batman's nemesis, The Joker and everyone knows I love the Batman.<br />Hugo is certainly not stingy with the written word, historical reference, or hyperbolic description of the most banal things. That is why I cherish him. But here he takes it to a nauseating degree: 100 pages of narrative describing a child walking up a hill coupled with an interminable shipwreck that you plead with him to end. Let them all die! you will scream to yourself in the abysmal void. Kill the kid while you're at it!<br />Oh wait, he is important! But you won't learn that for another 100 pages. Seriously, I'm not being glib. To get to the actual meat of the story, the titular freak, takes a good 1/3 of the novel. What precedes his appearance (by then you won't even care) is lengthy non-narrative descriptions of kings and things, smug entreaties to trivia, and very un-Hugo-like things.<br />Disappointed! (said in <i>that</i> voice)</span>
  <a data-text-id="12814950427865530441" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


